Question : https://leetcode.com/problems/create-target-array-in-the-given-order/description/
Solution : 
Approach 1 : 
Loop (building target ArrayList)
target.add(index[i], nums[i]): inserting at an arbitrary index in an ArrayList requires shifting elements to the right.
Worst case: O(n) per insertion.
For n elements → O(n²) in total.
Copying into result array
One pass through target: O(n).
Total Time Complexity = O(n²)

Space : 
target list stores up to n elements → O(n).
result array of size n → O(n).
Total Space Complexity = O(n)
 
class Solution {
    public int[] createTargetArray(int[] nums, int[] index) {
        List<Integer> target=new ArrayList<>();
        for(int i=0;i<index.length;i++){
            target.add(index[i],nums[i]);
        }
        int[] result = new int[target.size()];
        for (int i = 0; i < target.size(); i++) {
            result[i] = target.get(i);
        }
        return result;
    }
}

Approach 2:
Time Complexity = O(n²) Space Complexity = O(n)
class Solution {
    public int[] createTargetArray(int[] nums, int[] index) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int[] target = new int[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i; j > index[i]; j--) {
                target[j] = target[j - 1];
            }
            target[index[i]] = nums[i];
        }

        return target;
    }
}
